# Code Quality Standards - HIGHEST STANDARDS EXPECTED

## Core Principles

### 1. No Gold Plating

- **Implement only what is needed** - no speculative features or over-engineering
- Resist the urge to add "nice-to-have" features until they are actually required
- Focus on solving the immediate problem correctly and completely
- Every line of code should serve a clear, documented purpose

### 2. Follow Existing Repo Standards FIRST

- **Always use existing patterns, utilities, and standards** before creating new ones
- Search the codebase for similar implementations before writing new code
- Leverage existing packages in `packages/` directory
- Exceptions to existing patterns require explicit justification and team discussion

### 3. Extreme TypeScript Precision

- **Types must be extremely precise and correct** - no loose typing accepted
- Use literal types, and discriminated unions where appropriate
- Every function parameter and return type must be explicitly defined
- No implicit `any` types anywhere in the codebase
- Types should be as narrow and specific as possible

## ESLint Configuration Compliance

Our codebase follows strict ESLint rules. Key requirements:

### Forbidden Patterns

```typescript
// ❌ NEVER - Explicit any types
function process(data: any): any {}

// ❌ ALMOST NEVER - Double equals
if (value == undefined) {
}

// ❌ NEVER - var declarations
var something = 'value';

// ❌ NEVER - Unused variables
function example() {
    const unused = 'this will error'; // Must be used or prefixed with _
}

// ❌ NEVER - Default exports (warn level)
export default SomeClass;

// ❌ NEVER - Comma operator
const result = (doSomething(), getValue());
```

### Required Patterns

```typescript
// ✅ REQUIRED - Strict equality when distinguishing values
if (value === undefined) {
}

// ✅ PREFERRED - Truthiness / implicit checks when intent is "no value" (null, undefined, or empty string)
if (!token) {
    /* no token */
}
const hasToken = !!token;
// ❌ AVOID - Verbose explicit checks when truthiness expresses the same intent
if (token === null || token === undefined || token === '') {
}

// ✅ REQUIRED - let/const only
const immutableValue = 'value';
let mutableValue = 'value';

// ✅ REQUIRED - Named exports
export { SomeClass };

// ✅ REQUIRED - Type imports when used as types only
import type { SomeType } from './types.js';
import { someFunction } from './utils.js';

// ✅ REQUIRED - Underscore prefix for intentionally unused parameters
function callback(_unusedParam: string, usedParam: number) {
    return usedParam * 2;
}
```

### Prefer implicit (truthiness) checks when intent is "no value"

When the intent is simply "absent" or "falsy" (null, undefined, or empty string), use truthiness instead of spelling out each case:

- Use `!token` instead of `token === null || token === undefined || token === ''`.
- Use `if (token)` for "has value", `!!token` when you need a boolean.
- Use optional chaining and truthiness together where appropriate: `user?.name` then `if (!user?.name)`.

Use explicit `=== null` or `=== undefined` only when you need to distinguish between them (e.g. "undefined means unset, null means explicitly cleared").

## Naming Conventions (Enforced by Biome)

### Strict Case Requirements

```typescript
// ✅ Functions - strictCamelCase
function getUserData() {}
function processPaymentInfo() {}

// ✅ Variables - camelCase or PascalCase
const userData = {};
const PaymentProcessor = class {};

// ✅ Global constants - CONSTANT_CASE
const MAX_RETRY_ATTEMPTS = 3;
const API_BASE_URL = 'https://api.example.com';

// ✅ Types and interfaces - PascalCase
type UserProfile = { id: string; name: string };
interface PaymentRequest {
    amount: number;
    currency: string;
}

// ✅ Private class members - camelCase with optional underscore prefix
class Service {
    private _internalState = {};
    private processData() {}
}
```

### Semantic variable names (no single-letter names)

Always use semantic, descriptive variable names. Do not use single-letter names (e.g. `i`, `j`, `x`, `e`, `n`) even in short or simple functions—they hurt readability and searchability.

```typescript
// ✅ PREFERRED - Semantic names
const token = getStoredToken();
items.map((item) => item.id);
users.filter((user) => user.isActive);
catch (error) { ... }

// ❌ AVOID - Single-letter names
const t = getStoredToken();
items.map((i) => i.id);
users.filter((u) => u.isActive);
catch (e) { ... }
```

Exception: in very narrow mathematical or index contexts (e.g. `for (let i = 0; i < n; i++)` in a short loop), a single index letter may be acceptable, but prefer a descriptive name (e.g. `index`, `idx`) when it improves clarity.

## Type System Excellence

### Precision Requirements

```typescript
// ✅ EXCELLENT - Precise literal unions
type HttpMethod = 'GET' | 'POST' | 'PUT' | 'DELETE' | 'PATCH';
type LogLevel = 'debug' | 'info' | 'warn' | 'error' | 'fatal';

// ✅ EXCELLENT - Discriminated unions for state
type ApiResult<T> = { status: 'success'; data: T } | { status: 'error'; error: { code: string; message: string } };

// ❌ FORBIDDEN - Loose typing
type ApiResult = {
    status: string; // Too loose - should be literal union
    data?: any; // any is forbidden
    error?: object; // object is too loose
};
```

### Function Type Definitions

```typescript
// ✅ REQUIRED - Adjacent type definitions with type-fest utilities
import type { Branded, SetRequired, Exact } from 'type-fest';

type PaymentMethodId = Branded<string, 'PaymentMethodId'>;
type TransactionId = Branded<string, 'TransactionId'>;

type ProcessPaymentInput = {
    readonly amount: number;
    readonly currency: 'USD' | 'CAD' | 'EUR';
    readonly paymentMethodId: PaymentMethodId;
    readonly customerId: UserId;
};

type ProcessPaymentResult = ApiResult<{
    transactionId: TransactionId;
    status: 'approved' | 'declined' | 'pending';
    timestamp: Date;
}>;

export async function processPayment(input: ProcessPaymentInput): Promise<ProcessPaymentResult> {
    // Implementation
}

// ✅ EXCELLENT - Use type-fest for common transformations
type OptionalProcessPaymentInput = SetRequired<Partial<ProcessPaymentInput>, 'amount' | 'currency'>; // Makes all fields optional except amount and currency

// ❌ FORBIDDEN - Inline type definitions
export async function processPayment(input: {
    amount: number;
    currency: string;
    paymentMethodId: string;
    customerId: string;
}): Promise<{ success: boolean; data?: any }> {
    // This violates multiple standards
}
```

## Error Handling Excellence

### Offensive Programming

```typescript
// ❌ FORBIDDEN - Defensive programming that hides problems
export function calculatePercentage(value: any, total: any): number {
    // Converting silently hides type errors
    const numValue = Number(value) || 0;
    const numTotal = Number(total) || 1; // Silently avoiding division by zero
    return (numValue / numTotal) * 100;
}
```

## Repository Standards Compliance

### Use Existing Utilities FIRST

Before writing new code, check for existing solutions:

```typescript
// ❌ AVOID - Creating custom utilities that type-fest already provides
type MyCustomPartial<T> = { [K in keyof T]?: T[K] }; // Use PartialDeep instead
type MyCustomRequired<T> = { [K in keyof T]-?: T[K] }; // Use RequiredDeep instead
```

### Package Structure Compliance

```typescript
// ✅ REQUIRED - Index files as barrel exports only
// packages/my-feature/src/index.ts
export { processData } from './processData.js';
export { validateInput } from './validateInput.js';
export type { ProcessDataInput, ProcessDataResult } from './types.js';

// ✅ REQUIRED - Semantic file naming
// packages/my-feature/src/processData.ts - contains processData function
// packages/my-feature/src/validateInput.ts - contains validateInput function
// packages/my-feature/src/types.ts - contains type definitions
```

## Performance and Maintainability

### Switch Statements for Exhaustiveness

Use switch statements and exhaustive checking for unions

```typescript
// ❌ FORBIDDEN - Non-exhaustive if/else chains
function handleAction(action: Action): string {
    if (action === 'create') return 'Creating resource';
    if (action === 'update') return 'Updating resource';
    // Missing 'delete' case - TypeScript won't catch this
    return 'Unknown action';
}
```

## Code Quality Metrics

All code must meet these quality standards:

- **Type Coverage**: 100% - no implicit `any` types
- **Linting**: Zero ESLint errors or warnings
- **Unused Code**: Zero unused variables, imports, or functions
- **Naming**: 100% compliance with naming conventions
- **Documentation**: All public APIs must have JSDoc
- **Testing**: All business logic must have unit tests
- **Error Handling**: All error paths must be explicitly handled

## Quality Checklist

Before submitting code, ensure:

- [ ] All existing utilities and patterns have been considered first
- [ ] Types are as narrow and precise as possible
- [ ] No implicit `any` types exist
- [ ] All ESLint rules pass without warnings
- [ ] Proper error handling with Result pattern (for APIs)
- [ ] Exhaustive switch statements where applicable
- [ ] JSDoc documentation for all public functions
- [ ] Semantic file and function naming
- [ ] No unused code or imports
- [ ] No gold plating or speculative features
